67
00:04:20,750 --> 00:04:22,230
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, yeah, happy to.

68
00:04:22,250 --> 00:04:28,354
[SPEAKER_06]: So Diane, if you're all right, I have the doc here, I think probably easiest to share it out and run through that together.

69
00:04:29,614 --> 00:04:34,357
[SPEAKER_06]: Just for some context, the remit out of the last call was to

70
00:04:35,075 --> 00:04:42,482
[SPEAKER_06]: actually go through the ordinances that the city of Medford put in place to govern the Human Rights Commission.

71
00:04:43,863 --> 00:04:47,546
[SPEAKER_06]: We've been all, you know, coming together, meeting regularly for some time now.

72
00:04:48,647 --> 00:05:00,097
[SPEAKER_06]: And there was a desire to get a firm understanding of what the expectations and responsibilities were, and what the obligations are from a legal standpoint, to

73
00:05:00,463 --> 00:05:01,484
[SPEAKER_06]: put a fine point on it.

74
00:05:01,504 --> 00:05:08,729
[SPEAKER_06]: These are the governing ordinances that establish the commission and detail what is expected from and of the commission.

75
00:05:09,369 --> 00:05:18,235
[SPEAKER_06]: So what I'm going to share now is a Word doc, and it includes a link at the top here to the codes themselves.

76
00:05:18,435 --> 00:05:20,316
[SPEAKER_06]: And there's a lot of redundancy.

77
00:05:20,737 --> 00:05:28,162
[SPEAKER_06]: So you'll see, you might not be seeing if I'm only sharing the Word version, but

78
00:05:30,321 --> 00:05:34,622
[SPEAKER_06]: The way that I've broken this out mirrors exactly how the ordinance itself is broken out.

79
00:05:34,662 --> 00:05:46,206
[SPEAKER_06]: What I've tried to do is distill some of the language that is most pertinent, and then highlight those items that are tactical and strategic.

80
00:05:46,626 --> 00:05:49,047
[SPEAKER_06]: So by tactical, I'll just give a quick example.

81
00:05:50,387 --> 00:05:53,608
[SPEAKER_06]: The ordinance says there should be nine members, right?

82
00:05:53,628 --> 00:05:56,969
[SPEAKER_06]: That's specific, it's actionable, it's something that can be measured against.

83
00:05:57,598 --> 00:06:06,144
[SPEAKER_06]: There's other aspects that are a little bit more open to interpretation in terms of how best to act upon them.

84
00:06:06,625 --> 00:06:10,848
[SPEAKER_06]: So that's some of the way that you'll see the cascade organized here.

85
00:06:12,349 --> 00:06:25,719
[SPEAKER_06]: Working through it from top to bottom, and I can share this with the group as well after the call, really the items that you see with asterisks are points at which I think we can include

86
00:06:26,605 --> 00:06:29,646
[SPEAKER_06]: in our strategy or approach going forward.

87
00:06:30,466 --> 00:06:41,469
[SPEAKER_06]: And then also there are some pretty specific calls to action that I think we need to implement right away, simply for the fact that they're prescriptive in the ordinance.

88
00:06:42,029 --> 00:06:48,631
[SPEAKER_06]: So for fear of making everyone dizzy, I'll stop scrolling so quickly and just kind of run through things as they appear here.

89
00:06:49,191 --> 00:06:54,953
[SPEAKER_06]: So the first section establishes the grounds under which the

90
00:06:55,647 --> 00:06:58,009
[SPEAKER_06]: ordinance for the HRC rests.

91
00:06:58,430 --> 00:07:03,994
[SPEAKER_06]: And I should offer the caveat that I am in no way a legal expert, not an attorney.

92
00:07:04,255 --> 00:07:05,576
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't even play one on TV.

93
00:07:05,956 --> 00:07:15,805
[SPEAKER_06]: So this was simply my interpretation as a lay person, which since we're all lay people on the commission, I expect will be at least marginally helpful.

94
00:07:17,086 --> 00:07:20,609
[SPEAKER_06]: First and foremost, the commission is established to

95
00:07:21,325 --> 00:07:27,627
[SPEAKER_06]: ensure the free exercise and enjoyment of all rights and privileges enumerated in the Commonwealth and federal constitutions.

96
00:07:28,008 --> 00:07:36,831
[SPEAKER_06]: So key points there are that the be all end all the governing documents are the constitution in Massachusetts and the federal constitution.

97
00:07:37,171 --> 00:07:41,813
[SPEAKER_06]: So that's kind of the final backstop for any questions that we may have.

98
00:07:42,433 --> 00:07:46,535
[SPEAKER_06]: It articulates the relevant parties, all persons in

99
00:07:47,407 --> 00:07:50,148
[SPEAKER_06]: the city of Medford, which I think is an important distinction to make.

100
00:07:50,208 --> 00:07:51,369
[SPEAKER_06]: You don't need to be a resident.

101
00:07:51,449 --> 00:07:56,271
[SPEAKER_06]: You don't need to be in any way employed by the city or in the city.

102
00:07:56,331 --> 00:07:58,172
[SPEAKER_06]: It's anyone in the city.

103
00:07:58,792 --> 00:08:08,436
[SPEAKER_06]: And then of course, regardless of any type of contextual information or contextual biographical information on the relevant parties.

104
00:08:09,217 --> 00:08:14,459
[SPEAKER_06]: And these ordinances are enforceable anywhere.

105
00:08:14,579 --> 00:08:16,600
[SPEAKER_06]: There's unlawful discrimination.

106
00:08:17,606 --> 00:08:20,507
[SPEAKER_06]: This phrasing is repeated a couple of times.

107
00:08:20,527 --> 00:08:23,687
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm going to read through it once here, because I think it is important for the context.

108
00:08:23,707 --> 00:08:40,932
[SPEAKER_06]: It says, anywhere that discrimination exists in housing, employment, education, public accommodations, housing accommodations, and within the meaning of, and it refers to the Massachusetts General Laws, gives the chapter around anti-discrimination.

109
00:08:41,552 --> 00:08:47,173
[SPEAKER_06]: So my expectation is that this is meant to be as all-encompassing as possible.

110
00:08:47,563 --> 00:08:58,565
[SPEAKER_06]: But there needs to, of course, be some sort of gate around the enforceable jurisdiction, for lack of a better term.

111
00:09:00,146 --> 00:09:06,007
[SPEAKER_06]: If you dig into chapter 151B of the MGL, it's quite expansive.

112
00:09:06,387 --> 00:09:13,688
[SPEAKER_06]: So I don't expect that we would ever run into a situation where we would be coming up against a limitation on our jurisdiction.

113
00:09:15,489 --> 00:09:17,149
[SPEAKER_06]: This last point I think here is,

114
00:09:18,892 --> 00:09:20,012
[SPEAKER_06]: strong and operative.

115
00:09:20,713 --> 00:09:26,275
[SPEAKER_06]: It refers to the obligations that the city has to take reasonable affirmative action.

116
00:09:26,295 --> 00:09:29,576
[SPEAKER_06]: And, you know, affirmative action is somewhat of a loaded term.

117
00:09:29,616 --> 00:09:31,056
[SPEAKER_06]: Folks describe different meanings.

118
00:09:31,497 --> 00:09:33,277
[SPEAKER_06]: I took it here to be literal, right?

119
00:09:33,817 --> 00:09:41,600
[SPEAKER_06]: Affirmative action, taking action that is affirming the rights that are enumerated here rather than being reactive.

120
00:09:43,401 --> 00:09:46,042
[SPEAKER_06]: And those actions should be aimed towards

121
00:09:46,632 --> 00:09:53,537
[SPEAKER_06]: removing or empowering folks to overcome the consequences of any prior discriminatory practice.

122
00:09:55,359 --> 00:10:13,872
[SPEAKER_06]: And even go so far to articulate that in the absence of any prior discrimination, that if in administering previous programs, the outcome, the effect has been something that's been discriminatory, that that also falls under

123
00:10:15,920 --> 00:10:17,321
[SPEAKER_06]: the ordinance here and the guidelines.

124
00:10:18,181 --> 00:10:28,587
[SPEAKER_06]: I'll pause there before I get into my specific key takeaways, but anything to add, Diane or anyone else or any questions from the group?

125
00:10:31,689 --> 00:10:33,550
[SPEAKER_02]: No, I think you've covered it pretty well.

126
00:10:34,531 --> 00:10:35,431
[SPEAKER_06]: All right, great.

127
00:10:36,071 --> 00:10:42,315
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, pressing on then, I mentioned that I included in here some of my key takeaways intermittently throughout the report.

128
00:10:43,043 --> 00:10:45,505
[SPEAKER_06]: I've touched on some of these already, so I won't belabor the point.

129
00:10:45,525 --> 00:10:49,949
[SPEAKER_06]: But basically, the commission is in place to support all persons in the city.

130
00:10:49,969 --> 00:10:53,211
[SPEAKER_06]: The remit is very, very broad.

131
00:10:53,632 --> 00:11:02,899
[SPEAKER_06]: All of those different ways in which the city government touches the lives of folks that live, work, or are in the city.

132
00:11:03,760 --> 00:11:09,805
[SPEAKER_06]: And that there is a recognized obligation to take that affirmative action.

133
00:11:10,413 --> 00:11:13,034
[SPEAKER_06]: By the commission and through these ordinances.

134
00:11:14,275 --> 00:11:18,277
[SPEAKER_06]: The next couple sections are pretty specific.

135
00:11:18,517 --> 00:11:20,258
[SPEAKER_06]: So I have distilled them down quite a bit.

136
00:11:20,318 --> 00:11:26,742
[SPEAKER_06]: Again, the link is available at the top of this document to go to the full text version, but basically.

137
00:11:27,782 --> 00:11:33,065
[SPEAKER_06]: The way that the board or the commission is built.

138
00:11:36,373 --> 00:11:38,294
[SPEAKER_06]: described quite liberally.

139
00:11:38,354 --> 00:11:49,679
[SPEAKER_06]: There's a lot of room for interpretation so far as however the commission is constructed is aimed at accomplishing the purposes that we just went through.

140
00:11:50,179 --> 00:11:57,243
[SPEAKER_06]: In fact, the language in the ordinance itself stipulates that it is liberal in effect.

141
00:11:57,543 --> 00:12:00,044
[SPEAKER_06]: So it's intentional that that is the case.

142
00:12:00,084 --> 00:12:01,064
[SPEAKER_06]: It's not an inference there.

143
00:12:03,329 --> 00:12:11,753
[SPEAKER_06]: And that if there's any ordinances that are inconsistent with accomplishing the purposes of the HRC, they don't apply.

144
00:12:11,773 --> 00:12:21,398
[SPEAKER_06]: So basically, if there's something that exists somewhere else in code that we come up against, it's not applicable if it's in contradiction to the above.

145
00:12:22,504 --> 00:12:28,327
[SPEAKER_06]: And there's nothing that the HRC can do would contravene the laws of the Commonwealth.

146
00:12:28,347 --> 00:12:35,390
[SPEAKER_06]: So again, we come back to this point that the governing document, the Constitution for the Commonwealth of Massachusetts is that final backstop.

147
00:12:36,990 --> 00:12:39,692
[SPEAKER_06]: These next four points are specific and direct.

148
00:12:40,092 --> 00:12:45,074
[SPEAKER_06]: We need to have nine members, folks should, members need to live or work in the city,

149
00:12:45,783 --> 00:12:47,744
[SPEAKER_06]: The appointment process runs through the mayor.

150
00:12:47,884 --> 00:12:49,364
[SPEAKER_06]: I think we've all been through that.

151
00:12:49,504 --> 00:12:50,784
[SPEAKER_06]: I know I experienced that.

152
00:12:51,885 --> 00:13:02,207
[SPEAKER_06]: And that membership in the board should reflect a diverse representations of persons active in the efforts of human rights and civil rights activities in the city.

153
00:13:02,828 --> 00:13:07,789
[SPEAKER_06]: So I think some folks get hung up on the idea of diverse representation.

154
00:13:08,209 --> 00:13:15,291
[SPEAKER_06]: I think the further qualifier here is that individuals should be active in the efforts of human rights and civil rights activities within the city.

155
00:13:16,203 --> 00:13:20,486
[SPEAKER_06]: I do want to pause there because I think this can be a little bit cyclical, right?

156
00:13:20,646 --> 00:13:27,990
[SPEAKER_06]: If you're sitting here on the board, you're surely invested in efforts around human rights and civil rights activities in the city.

157
00:13:28,771 --> 00:13:36,476
[SPEAKER_06]: So I don't know if that is a prerequisite or something that's inherent in participation, possibly something we can clarify later.

158
00:13:37,236 --> 00:13:44,340
[SPEAKER_06]: In terms of the organizational structure within the commission, there is to be a chair, a vice chair, and a clerk.

159
00:13:45,920 --> 00:13:50,644
[SPEAKER_06]: I want to put a fine point on that, that this is not like general guidance or nice to have.

160
00:13:51,025 --> 00:13:54,107
[SPEAKER_06]: This is what appears in the ordinance that establishes the ASRC.

161
00:13:54,648 --> 00:13:58,311
[SPEAKER_06]: So we did well to have those elections recently.

162
00:13:59,552 --> 00:14:02,515
[SPEAKER_06]: They should be every other year in June.

163
00:14:03,495 --> 00:14:08,660
[SPEAKER_06]: And that goes hand in glove with the idea that those terms are for two years.

164
00:14:11,860 --> 00:14:14,142
[SPEAKER_06]: you can run two consecutive terms.

165
00:14:14,642 --> 00:14:18,705
[SPEAKER_06]: So you can be in an elected position for up to four years is how I took that.

166
00:14:20,626 --> 00:14:40,440
[SPEAKER_06]: There were also specific guidelines around participation and the fact that anyone who is missing more than two meetings in a fiscal year, other than for excused absences, I'll call them, the commission should take it unto itself to review that individual's commitment.

167
00:14:41,122 --> 00:14:48,365
[SPEAKER_06]: That's left open to interpretation, but something that I think should be highlighted here.

168
00:14:49,225 --> 00:14:58,228
[SPEAKER_06]: And that additional terms can be served as long as there is a one-year gap between serving those terms.

169
00:14:58,348 --> 00:15:09,492
[SPEAKER_06]: So this was a little bit confusing because of how it was laid out in the initial document, but I took it to be pertinent to the elected positions.

170
00:15:11,465 --> 00:15:25,109
[SPEAKER_06]: So thinking here that there could be a situation where maybe taking a step back, the one year off from serving is a little bit confusing because they're saying that the elected position should be two year terms.

171
00:15:25,789 --> 00:15:38,233
[SPEAKER_06]: I think that this is in the instance where somebody removes themselves, where they step back partway through a new elected position is filled and

172
00:15:39,070 --> 00:15:43,853
[SPEAKER_06]: there is a one-year vacancy there between the previous elected official.

173
00:15:44,153 --> 00:15:50,797
[SPEAKER_06]: They can then fill that role as long as there's been a full year in between the two seedings, as it were.

174
00:15:50,817 --> 00:15:58,301
[SPEAKER_06]: I highlight here that the language was a little bit confusing and it doesn't delineate.

175
00:15:58,341 --> 00:16:01,983
[SPEAKER_06]: I took it as fair to assume that it refers to the officers.

176
00:16:02,004 --> 00:16:04,625
[SPEAKER_06]: It could be something that we want to get specific direction on.

177
00:16:04,645 --> 00:16:07,487
[SPEAKER_06]: Then I'll circle back to something I put in the

178
00:16:08,975 --> 00:16:11,317
[SPEAKER_06]: In the doc a little bit later on as well.

179
00:16:14,139 --> 00:16:15,360
[SPEAKER_06]: This isn't so relevant.

180
00:16:15,940 --> 00:16:21,124
[SPEAKER_06]: It speaks to the initial appointment of members to the commission when it was established.

181
00:16:21,424 --> 00:16:32,713
[SPEAKER_06]: So basically those initial appointments were to follow a staggered schedule and basically sink out on three year terms after that initial group was put in place.

182
00:16:34,234 --> 00:16:36,956
[SPEAKER_06]: And if there is a situation where somebody leaves,

183
00:16:38,953 --> 00:16:43,035
[SPEAKER_06]: Those seats need to be filled by appointment as well.

184
00:16:43,055 --> 00:16:45,817
[SPEAKER_06]: You can't circumvent that appointment by the mayor.

185
00:16:47,978 --> 00:16:52,981
[SPEAKER_06]: I've gone through quite a bit and I've talked at you for about 15 minutes now without reprieve.

186
00:16:53,001 --> 00:16:55,402
[SPEAKER_05]: So I'll pause again and ask if there's any questions or thoughts.

187
00:16:58,343 --> 00:16:58,764
[SPEAKER_05]: All right.

188
00:16:59,724 --> 00:17:01,865
[SPEAKER_05]: Must mean I'm doing an excellent job explaining.

189
00:17:01,885 --> 00:17:04,907
[SPEAKER_06]: That's how I'll take that anyway.

190
00:17:05,187 --> 00:17:06,728
[SPEAKER_06]: More prescriptive guidance here.

191
00:17:07,734 --> 00:17:08,975
[SPEAKER_06]: meetings and quorums.

192
00:17:09,655 --> 00:17:12,777
[SPEAKER_06]: So 10 meetings a year, that's a cadence that we've kept up with.

193
00:17:12,977 --> 00:17:16,039
[SPEAKER_06]: We interpret that to mean a break in the summer months.

194
00:17:16,539 --> 00:17:18,240
[SPEAKER_06]: That's not prescribed anywhere.

195
00:17:18,280 --> 00:17:19,621
[SPEAKER_06]: That's open to interpretation.

196
00:17:20,381 --> 00:17:22,603
[SPEAKER_06]: It just indicates that they need to be in regular intervals.

197
00:17:22,683 --> 00:17:27,225
[SPEAKER_06]: So if we wanted to move, say, to meeting every six weeks, it's not a recommendation, just an example.

198
00:17:27,625 --> 00:17:30,267
[SPEAKER_06]: That can be another way to get 10 meetings in a year.

199
00:17:30,287 --> 00:17:34,669
[SPEAKER_06]: I guess it would have to be every 5.2 weeks, but we'll get into that later.

200
00:17:36,188 --> 00:17:38,150
[SPEAKER_06]: five members constitute a quorum.

201
00:17:39,190 --> 00:17:44,114
[SPEAKER_06]: I highlight this below, but that five member quorum is static.

202
00:17:44,874 --> 00:17:49,117
[SPEAKER_06]: And of course it's predicated on the idea that there are nine members on the commission.

203
00:17:50,038 --> 00:18:01,246
[SPEAKER_06]: So that is certainly a point that I think we need to address given the level of engagement and the number of commissioners we have now, because technically speaking, as I read it as a non-legal professional,

204
00:18:04,173 --> 00:18:13,977
[SPEAKER_06]: We've never had a quorum, then, because we've never had a nine-member, fully seated, filled commission, and five of those nine members present.

205
00:18:15,018 --> 00:18:17,699
[SPEAKER_07]: Excuse me, Rob.

206
00:18:17,839 --> 00:18:20,960
[SPEAKER_07]: I think your statement says we've never had a quorum?

207
00:18:23,182 --> 00:18:44,985
[SPEAKER_06]: Under these guidelines, if nine members are required to meet the five-member quorum, and the five-member quorum is required to have a quorum, as long as I've been in panel, we've never had nine members, which I think to your point, Muneer, it's a little bit of like chicken and egg, legal hopscotch here, simply highlighting it because I think it is something that we should address.

208
00:18:47,735 --> 00:18:57,119
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, yeah, no, I mean, I sort of interpreted that as, okay, there should be nine members, okay, but a quorum is separate from that.

209
00:18:57,219 --> 00:19:01,801
[SPEAKER_07]: A quorum is, they're specifying that you need five members to have a quorum.

210
00:19:02,542 --> 00:19:10,005
[SPEAKER_07]: And we've met that, of course, problem last year several times, but, and indeed, it should be reviewed.

211
00:19:10,743 --> 00:19:32,490
[SPEAKER_07]: But I think to say that we've never had a quorum is a little confusing in the sense that, okay, we have right now six members, I guess, but we're still restricted by the fact that if we don't have five members, then we don't have a quorum and then we can't vote on anything.

212
00:19:32,970 --> 00:19:33,910
[SPEAKER_07]: Sorry for the interruption.

213
00:19:34,430 --> 00:19:34,850
[SPEAKER_06]: No, no.

214
00:19:35,471 --> 00:19:35,811
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

215
00:19:35,831 --> 00:19:38,492
[SPEAKER_06]: That was unclear the way that I laid it out.

216
00:19:38,612 --> 00:19:39,932
[SPEAKER_06]: I appreciate the clarification.

217
00:19:41,109 --> 00:20:09,140
[SPEAKER_06]: And another good point that was brought up here is around the structures and rules for subcommittees considering this requirement for a quorum and what we might be able to do to have something like a standing approval for subcommittees so that work can take place within subcommittees without requiring a five-member quorum always be present for any definitive

218
00:20:10,186 --> 00:20:12,508
[SPEAKER_06]: action to be taken or any discussion to be had.

219
00:20:13,509 --> 00:20:17,052
[SPEAKER_06]: This is something I think that bears certainly further conversation amongst the group.

220
00:20:17,712 --> 00:20:21,135
[SPEAKER_06]: And I'll leave it at that.

