00:20:39,549 --> 00:20:44,513
[SPEAKER_03]: you know, simple amendments to this that would just make sense.

226
00:20:44,653 --> 00:20:50,738
[SPEAKER_03]: And I know that, you know, Kelly and I are thinking through roles and responsibilities.

227
00:20:50,818 --> 00:20:59,626
[SPEAKER_03]: So she and I are working on, I started a spreadsheet by researching other human rights commissions in the greater Boston area.

228
00:21:00,506 --> 00:21:04,550
[SPEAKER_03]: And, and, you know, I read an ordinance where

229
00:21:05,422 --> 00:21:10,387
[SPEAKER_03]: working groups and subcommittees were baked into the ordinance so that people could get work done.

230
00:21:10,407 --> 00:21:20,899
[SPEAKER_03]: And then I'm trying to remember it was either Boston or Malden, they had, instead of using quorum, you know, for their quorum,

231
00:21:21,983 --> 00:21:32,287
[SPEAKER_03]: They must have had the same challenge that we're experiencing because instead of having a finite number of what constitutes a quorum, they just have the word majority.

232
00:21:33,107 --> 00:21:49,012
[SPEAKER_03]: So I know that next meeting, I would love to have Kelly and I present our research because I think it will really help, but I don't wanna get off topic, Rob, but you're doing a great job, so thank you.

233
00:21:49,032 --> 00:21:51,153
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

234
00:21:51,565 --> 00:21:53,106
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, I think that's a great point.

235
00:21:53,766 --> 00:22:05,290
[SPEAKER_06]: You shouldn't use the language as an excuse not to interpret it in the way that most effectively empowers the commission to act.

236
00:22:05,350 --> 00:22:13,613
[SPEAKER_06]: I think that circles back to the initial point that was laid out about the regulations being liberal in nature.

237
00:22:13,633 --> 00:22:18,554
[SPEAKER_06]: The intent is that these are enabling rather than constricting.

238
00:22:18,874 --> 00:22:20,815
[SPEAKER_05]: So I definitely agree.

239
00:22:27,140 --> 00:22:29,281
[SPEAKER_05]: This next section is pretty much verbatim.

240
00:22:30,422 --> 00:22:34,545
[SPEAKER_06]: It gets into some pretty specific legal language.

241
00:22:34,585 --> 00:22:36,827
[SPEAKER_06]: So I didn't do a whole lot of editing here.

242
00:22:36,867 --> 00:22:40,730
[SPEAKER_06]: I really just broke it out to make it a little bit more easy to digest.

243
00:22:41,330 --> 00:22:50,898
[SPEAKER_06]: But what you see here are the functions and the powers that are given to the commission through these ordinances.

244
00:22:51,602 --> 00:23:06,095
[SPEAKER_06]: And rather than read through them all, I think the items that I've highlighted are the specific action items, things like eliminating unlawful discrimination, cultivating atmospheres of mutual understanding.

245
00:23:06,815 --> 00:23:12,360
[SPEAKER_06]: I'll move somewhat slowly here so folks can read those as we move down.

246
00:23:12,500 --> 00:23:16,724
[SPEAKER_06]: But there are some thoughts that I had around

