00:46:26,855 --> 00:46:41,421
[SPEAKER_07]: And we had a, we actually, we had, when I first joined, we had a detailed discussion among the board members of other commissioners, I should say, of how to handle discrimination.

438
00:46:42,602 --> 00:46:42,762
[SPEAKER_07]: And

439
00:46:44,315 --> 00:46:49,938
[SPEAKER_07]: and we established a procedure and we more or less followed it.

440
00:46:49,958 --> 00:46:58,742
[SPEAKER_07]: Of course, the city never specified a definite procedure on how to handle this.

441
00:46:59,282 --> 00:47:10,988
[SPEAKER_07]: So the commission itself established this procedure and we used it, I would say on few occasions

442
00:47:11,923 --> 00:47:15,644
[SPEAKER_07]: that there were a few occasions where we did receive complaints.

443
00:47:17,884 --> 00:47:33,547
[SPEAKER_07]: I would say mostly the work was initially done by the DEI director, at that time it was Neil, and with some assistance from the chair.

444
00:47:35,067 --> 00:47:41,248
[SPEAKER_07]: And we never actually resolved any of the complaints.

445
00:47:42,357 --> 00:47:55,144
[SPEAKER_07]: Because, I mean, I guess even if we did have to resolve them one way or the other, there is no way in the state that the commission has the power to enforce such a resolution.

446
00:47:56,184 --> 00:47:59,926
[SPEAKER_07]: So then what comes, so there are two things going on.

447
00:48:00,486 --> 00:48:04,128
[SPEAKER_07]: There is the ordinance established certain things.

448
00:48:04,829 --> 00:48:11,072
[SPEAKER_07]: There are discussions internally within the Human Rights Commission to decide how practically to do these things.

449
00:48:11,878 --> 00:48:22,568
[SPEAKER_07]: And then as Judy pointed out, the new administration, newer administration four years ago, decided on its own procedure to handle complaints.

450
00:48:23,389 --> 00:48:27,512
[SPEAKER_07]: And it kind of marginalized the Human Rights Commission.

451
00:48:27,672 --> 00:48:31,336
[SPEAKER_07]: So this is the situation that we're in.

452
00:48:31,916 --> 00:48:35,860
[SPEAKER_07]: So we have to decide on whether we wanna

453
00:48:36,751 --> 00:48:47,618
[SPEAKER_07]: go on with this procedure, you know, that's dictated by the city, even though it's marginalized the HRC, or we can say, no, we don't want to handle complaints at all.

454
00:48:48,238 --> 00:48:48,538
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay.

455
00:48:48,958 --> 00:48:58,584
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean, again, that's, that's to me, it's an open discussion and, and we, we need to decide which way to go.

456
00:49:02,947 --> 00:49:04,988
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, I think that, I mean, we work in,

457
00:49:05,628 --> 00:49:08,569
[SPEAKER_03]: We work in collaboration with the city.

458
00:49:08,629 --> 00:49:12,791
[SPEAKER_03]: We're appointed by the mayor and Francis.

459
00:49:14,311 --> 00:49:15,652
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, we're appointed by the mayor.

460
00:49:15,692 --> 00:49:20,433
[SPEAKER_03]: We work closely and keep Francis fully apprised.

461
00:49:21,774 --> 00:49:27,636
[SPEAKER_03]: And I do know from my own line of work in community building that it is effective.

462
00:49:27,656 --> 00:49:33,338
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, obviously we wouldn't have the pat like a ton of power to really

463
00:49:34,374 --> 00:49:54,781
[SPEAKER_03]: decide on full resolution, but it always makes a difference when community member, you know, Medford resident to Medford resident, we can sit like we're the Human Rights Commission, we're going to listen to you, we get you, we understand you, any one of us, you know, we're in it together.

464
00:49:54,941 --> 00:49:58,082
[SPEAKER_03]: And even that can usually help, um,

465
00:49:59,432 --> 00:50:06,856
[SPEAKER_03]: de-escalate stress and tension that whoever is issuing the grievance is experiencing.

466
00:50:07,116 --> 00:50:15,861
[SPEAKER_03]: So I do think having this role is probably a good thing for our residents and community.

467
00:50:20,523 --> 00:50:26,167
[SPEAKER_06]: I certainly want to voice support for the commission taking on that role.

468
00:50:26,347 --> 00:50:28,828
[SPEAKER_06]: I think, not to belabor the point, but

469
00:50:29,272 --> 00:50:31,374
[SPEAKER_06]: to reemphasize Diane, you're exactly right.

470
00:50:31,454 --> 00:50:46,827
[SPEAKER_06]: And in many cases, the act of being heard is the most impactful piece of restorative justice for folks who feel as though they've been a victim of injustice.

471
00:50:47,467 --> 00:50:56,455
[SPEAKER_06]: And I think that whatever we take out of this, we should certainly position ourselves to be helping that process within the city.

472
00:51:10,987 --> 00:51:11,648
[SPEAKER_04]: Go ahead, Aileen.

