00:51:19,574 --> 00:51:20,314
[SPEAKER_04]: Aileen, go for it.

474
00:51:20,995 --> 00:51:23,957
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, I see your hand raised if you're still wanting to share thoughts.

475
00:51:25,738 --> 00:51:26,079
[SPEAKER_10]: OK.

476
00:51:26,679 --> 00:51:30,982
[SPEAKER_10]: So my reaction is, I know it's important for people to be heard.

477
00:51:31,002 --> 00:51:31,983
[SPEAKER_10]: I agree.

478
00:51:32,664 --> 00:51:37,627
[SPEAKER_10]: But when people are heard, they have an expectation that there will be action.

479
00:51:38,808 --> 00:51:48,773
[SPEAKER_10]: And if there is no enforcement power that the commission holds, then it will be a frustration to the people who come.

480
00:51:48,973 --> 00:51:50,313
[SPEAKER_10]: I have seen that happen.

481
00:51:50,733 --> 00:51:53,335
[SPEAKER_10]: I saw that happen on the disability commission.

482
00:51:53,955 --> 00:51:56,956
[SPEAKER_10]: A woman came with a complaint about the post office.

483
00:51:57,897 --> 00:52:04,420
[SPEAKER_10]: And then she was told, well, you know, the post office is under the federal government, so we can't do anything.

484
00:52:05,501 --> 00:52:11,146
[SPEAKER_10]: And she went away very unhappy, even though that was a logical explanation.

485
00:52:11,206 --> 00:52:21,755
[SPEAKER_10]: But I just think, in my opinion, if you don't have enforcement, if there's nothing you can do, people are going to see it as a farce.

486
00:52:22,495 --> 00:52:25,057
[SPEAKER_10]: And I could be wrong, but that's my opinion.

487
00:52:27,439 --> 00:52:28,140
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you, Aileen.

488
00:52:28,160 --> 00:52:31,162
[SPEAKER_04]: I think I also, oh, sorry, Kelly.

