496
00:53:10,157 --> 00:53:23,230
[SPEAKER_04]: the capacity to sort of see conversations through and offer a deliverable or an outcome that is, I don't know, that is, you know, quality enough.

497
00:53:23,350 --> 00:53:29,837
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't know how to say that, but that, you know, the person in question finds commensurate with their experience or whatever.

498
00:53:35,358 --> 00:53:38,700
[SPEAKER_11]: Yeah, I was kind of going to say, sorry, Shelly.

499
00:53:39,960 --> 00:53:45,503
[SPEAKER_11]: I was going to say, you know, I'm, I'm really big into restorative justice practices.

500
00:53:45,563 --> 00:53:47,884
[SPEAKER_11]: I actually do them a lot in my elementary school.

501
00:53:48,465 --> 00:53:55,368
[SPEAKER_11]: And I think that there, there is a piece where you do need the other parties involvement.

502
00:53:56,069 --> 00:54:00,251
[SPEAKER_11]: So to, to, to really make it be a situation where people feel

503
00:54:01,637 --> 00:54:04,699
[SPEAKER_11]: heard and valued and listened, that repair piece has to happen.

504
00:54:04,739 --> 00:54:23,111
[SPEAKER_11]: And we don't have if we don't have the power or ability to, you know, help repairs happen and make amends and apology of actions and things of that nature just feels to me kind of fruitless.

505
00:54:24,823 --> 00:54:30,586
[SPEAKER_11]: I understand that, and Diane, to your point, I do feel like being heard is huge and valid.

506
00:54:30,846 --> 00:54:36,609
[SPEAKER_11]: And I also feel like that might not be the place for it here.

507
00:54:36,889 --> 00:54:37,350
[SPEAKER_11]: I don't know.

508
00:54:37,370 --> 00:54:38,050
[SPEAKER_11]: I don't know.

509
00:54:41,311 --> 00:54:42,832
[SPEAKER_07]: So can I add one thing?

510
00:54:42,852 --> 00:54:43,673
[SPEAKER_07]: Of course.

511
00:54:44,153 --> 00:54:44,553
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay.

512
00:54:45,354 --> 00:54:52,117
[SPEAKER_07]: So, I mean, the ability to be heard is not as simple as that.

513
00:54:53,467 --> 00:55:19,036
[SPEAKER_07]: So when I've been involved in like two or three complaints that were brought forward, the procedure that we established initially said that the two parties will communicate with the DEI director and with some involvement of a committee or a subcommittee of the human rights.

514
00:55:20,308 --> 00:55:27,494
[SPEAKER_07]: In other words, the complaints were never publicly heard because there were some privacy issues.

515
00:55:29,536 --> 00:55:44,790
[SPEAKER_07]: And only at the stage where both parties agree that, yes, you can come to a meeting of the HRC and it's a public meeting and both of you are heard,

516
00:55:45,327 --> 00:55:49,490
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, only then we decided that that would happen.

517
00:55:50,070 --> 00:55:54,814
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, but frankly, practically speaking, in none of the cases this ever happened.

518
00:55:55,835 --> 00:56:07,983
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, so it's not as in other words, it would be ideal if yes, the complaint can be heard and people know about it, but there are other restrictions as well.

519
00:56:09,144 --> 00:56:10,405
[SPEAKER_07]: That's part of the problem.

520
00:56:11,906 --> 00:56:13,107
[SPEAKER_04]: Thanks, Chief Chapman.

521
00:56:15,125 --> 00:56:20,187
[SPEAKER_00]: So actually, Muneer, I'll start with Muneer's point because it was one of the ones I wanted to make.

522
00:56:20,267 --> 00:56:24,988
[SPEAKER_00]: One of the problems I think we're always going to contend with is we have to meet as a public body, right?

523
00:56:25,048 --> 00:56:28,849
[SPEAKER_00]: And then we want to try to bring two people together, whether it's for mediation or to be heard.

524
00:56:29,510 --> 00:56:32,691
[SPEAKER_00]: That in and of itself is a barrier to some people and their compliance.

525
00:56:32,731 --> 00:56:35,031
[SPEAKER_00]: And we have to kind of keep that in mind going forward.

526
00:56:36,092 --> 00:56:39,273
[SPEAKER_00]: But going back to my original thought is,

527
00:56:40,640 --> 00:56:45,801
[SPEAKER_00]: I think the ordinance is written in a certain way, and I do think it needs a lot of work.

528
00:56:46,221 --> 00:56:51,042
[SPEAKER_00]: The question was raised by Rob earlier, should we reach out to the city council?

529
00:56:51,062 --> 00:56:59,424
[SPEAKER_00]: I think most definitely you should have city councils involved in this process from the beginning, because they can start through their subcommittees and sort of get involved in the process.

530
00:56:59,464 --> 00:57:04,865
[SPEAKER_00]: At least they're in the ground floor as the ordinance kind of changes and moves forward.

531
00:57:05,305 --> 00:57:06,545
[SPEAKER_00]: We started this process,

532
00:57:07,525 --> 00:57:12,966
[SPEAKER_00]: of what we're doing now in the review of the HRC because we kind of lost our way and we didn't know what our way was or our direction.

533
00:57:13,667 --> 00:57:17,088
[SPEAKER_00]: And slowly but surely at every meeting, we're getting there, right?

534
00:57:17,128 --> 00:57:17,848
[SPEAKER_00]: We're defining it.

535
00:57:18,828 --> 00:57:21,689
[SPEAKER_00]: But I think the ordinance probably has to look at that in and of itself.

536
00:57:21,789 --> 00:57:26,630
[SPEAKER_00]: I think there are expectations written into that ordinance that lead to disappointment.

537
00:57:26,730 --> 00:57:34,552
[SPEAKER_00]: I can go to the HRC, I can express my grievance against XYZ and expect something to happen.

538
00:57:35,333 --> 00:57:36,733
[SPEAKER_00]: And we talk about enforcement.

539
00:57:37,728 --> 00:57:46,886
[SPEAKER_00]: We may not have authority to enforce certain things but we certainly have the authority to advocate, and maybe that should be clearly written in there that.

540
00:57:48,261 --> 00:57:51,362
[SPEAKER_00]: If we can't do something, we can advocate on your behalf.

541
00:57:51,422 --> 00:58:05,248
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think when we write this ordinance, if we think in terms of this and we're very clear about what we can do, more people will, at least from the outset, will kind of understand what is expected of their involvement with the HRC.

542
00:58:05,268 --> 00:58:06,808
[SPEAKER_00]: So I just wanted to put those two cents in there.

543
00:58:06,828 --> 00:58:16,572
[SPEAKER_00]: I mean, there can be other things that we can do other than enforcement and have positive outcomes, at least for those coming before us.

544
00:58:21,754 --> 00:58:23,875
[SPEAKER_02]: That's helpful to hear Chief Buckley.

545
00:58:24,015 --> 00:58:44,724
[SPEAKER_03]: And I think that, you know, again, in this, you know, light research that I've already done, it just seems to be standard operating procedure for the Human Rights Commissions across a number of these towns to be available to residents for, you know, in the context of human rights grievances, so.

546
00:58:44,744 --> 00:58:48,065
[SPEAKER_04]: Diane, are those rules also volunteer-based?

547
00:58:50,060 --> 00:58:51,761
[SPEAKER_03]: Are those roles also volunteer?

548
00:58:53,022 --> 00:58:57,445
[SPEAKER_03]: The majority of them were so I'm in the middle of putting together a spreadsheet.

549
00:58:57,926 --> 00:58:59,167
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

550
00:58:59,347 --> 00:59:08,934
[SPEAKER_03]: I'll continue to I'll have it further fleshed out for our next meeting and then and I'll share it with you Kelly and then we can present on it.

551
00:59:09,994 --> 00:59:10,235
[SPEAKER_04]: Sure.

552
00:59:10,315 --> 00:59:16,139
[SPEAKER_04]: I just I also hear Rob's point that this is also potentially a platform to really overhaul what

553
00:59:16,770 --> 00:59:19,833
[SPEAKER_04]: you know, Commissioner can or should or might or would mean.

554
00:59:19,853 --> 00:59:38,508
[SPEAKER_06]: Um, so I suppose coming out of all this, certainly we've had an inspired conversation here.

555
00:59:38,528 --> 00:59:45,434
[SPEAKER_06]: It sounds to me as though there's at least some consensus that

556
00:59:47,182 --> 00:59:52,464
[SPEAKER_06]: either the way that we operate or the ordinance itself needs to be overhauled.

557
00:59:55,445 --> 01:00:02,407
[SPEAKER_06]: Personally, my thought is that looping in at this stage, council makes the most sense.

558
01:00:03,007 --> 01:00:13,430
[SPEAKER_06]: I think that whether it be lay people trying to craft civil code or trying to interpret civil code, it is not often a recipe for success.

559
01:00:13,450 --> 01:00:14,551
[SPEAKER_06]: So

560
01:00:16,842 --> 01:00:28,707
[SPEAKER_06]: The question then is given the situation, as I understand it, with the city solicitor in Medford, that there is not one at current, or if that's changed, you know, all the better.

561
01:00:29,408 --> 01:00:43,234
[SPEAKER_06]: But I'm curious to know from the group, what we think is the best next step given that situation, if there's an organization, I think I've heard of before, that's a retainer with the city, if their services are appropriate here, if it makes the most sense,

562
01:00:44,173 --> 01:00:56,256
[SPEAKER_06]: However unfortunate it might be to wait for someone to fill that seat to endeavor after substantial changes here and to focus on the things that we can change in the meantime.

563
01:00:57,836 --> 01:01:05,758
[SPEAKER_06]: But all of this being aimed towards eventually, I think, making some motion for some action so that we continue forward.

564
01:01:05,879 --> 01:01:11,400
[SPEAKER_06]: I think those are kind of the options as I see them at this point and that's meant to be.

565
01:01:12,529 --> 01:01:15,450
[SPEAKER_06]: an opening for conversation rather than a declarative statement.

566
01:01:17,751 --> 01:01:18,271
[SPEAKER_04]: Thanks, Rob.

567
01:01:23,233 --> 01:01:31,376
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, so I myself personally, I don't want to get hung up on waiting for a solicitor.

568
01:01:31,876 --> 01:01:36,578
[SPEAKER_07]: And I think the role of the solicitor would only enter at the very end.

569
01:01:37,663 --> 01:01:45,729
[SPEAKER_07]: when and if a new ordinance is written, then the solicitor has to say, yeah, this is legal, this is not legal, blah, blah, blah.

570
01:01:46,509 --> 01:01:50,352
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, so I think we do what we can.

571
01:01:50,612 --> 01:01:52,073
[SPEAKER_07]: We study the ordinance.

572
01:01:53,174 --> 01:01:56,396
[SPEAKER_07]: We decide, do we want to make some changes?

573
01:01:56,416 --> 01:01:58,478
[SPEAKER_07]: Do we want to make certain recommendations?

574
01:01:59,138 --> 01:02:00,679
[SPEAKER_07]: And then go forward with that.

575
01:02:01,520 --> 01:02:05,783
[SPEAKER_07]: That's at least my two cents on this process.

576
01:02:06,908 --> 01:02:07,689
[SPEAKER_04]: Thanks, Muneer.

577
01:02:08,389 --> 01:02:09,630
[SPEAKER_04]: Judy, you have your hand raised.

578
01:02:10,551 --> 01:02:11,452
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah.

579
01:02:12,272 --> 01:02:17,717
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm going to send you my edit from last October.

580
01:02:17,737 --> 01:02:29,666
[SPEAKER_09]: I just want to let you know that the underlying document, the underlying Word document may look different from the ordinance that you folks were looking at.

581
01:02:30,147 --> 01:02:36,512
[SPEAKER_09]: Because at one point, Neil accepted a lot of edits that I had made of the document.

582
01:02:37,284 --> 01:02:45,268
[SPEAKER_09]: So it is possible that this is actually a later version with some additional edits from last October.

583
01:02:45,488 --> 01:02:47,449
[SPEAKER_09]: Is that clear?

584
01:02:48,750 --> 01:02:53,352
[SPEAKER_09]: I mean, the original one was a copy of a copy of a copy of a copy.

585
01:02:53,532 --> 01:03:03,477
[SPEAKER_09]: And at one point, somehow we got hold of a PDF and I converted it to Word and Neil did,

586
01:03:05,365 --> 01:03:07,467
[SPEAKER_09]: except quite a few of my changes.

587
01:03:07,567 --> 01:03:19,399
[SPEAKER_09]: So this is that document with some additional comments from me, some of which I just this moment updated.

588
01:03:20,620 --> 01:03:27,527
[SPEAKER_09]: The other thing I want to ask is, you know, is that Safe Medford has a committee that has offered to be of assistance

589
01:03:28,709 --> 01:03:40,278
[SPEAKER_09]: and just want to go back to the Safe Medford Committee with, you know, what this group's position is on that offer of assistance.

590
01:03:44,462 --> 01:03:45,263
[SPEAKER_04]: Sure.

591
01:03:45,983 --> 01:03:47,545
[SPEAKER_04]: Do you want to speak to that?

592
01:03:47,625 --> 01:03:49,887
[SPEAKER_04]: Or maybe Steve or Munir, do folks want to jump in?

593
01:03:59,721 --> 01:04:03,224
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean, Steve, were you about to say something?

594
01:04:04,085 --> 01:04:04,806
[SPEAKER_07]: I yield to you.

595
01:04:07,708 --> 01:04:13,234
[SPEAKER_07]: Don't yield that easily next time.

596
01:04:13,674 --> 01:04:18,979
[SPEAKER_07]: OK, so I think this is going to be an ongoing process.

597
01:04:20,560 --> 01:04:25,245
[SPEAKER_07]: We, I mean, I'm sort of on both

598
01:04:26,793 --> 01:04:32,958
[SPEAKER_07]: both committees, I'm both a commissioner and on the Safe Medford Committee.

599
01:04:33,459 --> 01:04:50,655
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean, the Safe Medford Committee basically was looking at the practical things that the HRC was doing or was not doing and decided, well, let's take a look at this and see how we can make the HRC more effective.

600
01:04:51,850 --> 01:04:56,152
[SPEAKER_07]: And as a result of that, they came up with some recommendations.

601
01:04:57,113 --> 01:05:00,494
[SPEAKER_07]: And these recommendations were made to the Human Rights Commission.

602
01:05:01,575 --> 01:05:11,020
[SPEAKER_07]: So it is up to the commission to say, okay, we will look at these recommendations, okay, and totally ignore them.

603
01:05:12,120 --> 01:05:19,984
[SPEAKER_07]: Or we will look at these recommendations and say, hmm, there are certain things that make sense for us to pursue.

604
01:05:21,355 --> 01:05:23,997
[SPEAKER_07]: Uh, and, uh, and then we will do so.

605
01:05:24,758 --> 01:05:29,202
[SPEAKER_07]: So, and I think in a sense, that's what we're doing right now.

606
01:05:30,603 --> 01:05:41,572
[SPEAKER_07]: Uh, so, so, so, so that that's, that's, that's my, so, so, so I guess we as a commission have to decide on how to proceed, how to go forward.

607
01:05:41,972 --> 01:05:49,859
[SPEAKER_07]: Do we want to spend a lot of time studying the ordinance, changing, tweaking, tweaking it, making it better?

608
01:05:50,653 --> 01:06:05,839
[SPEAKER_07]: Or do we want to say, well, this is all good and dandy, but we also have some other work as a commission that we wanna do in this coming year and the next year and so on, and possibly unload some of the work on someone else.

609
01:06:06,960 --> 01:06:12,722
[SPEAKER_07]: So this is, I think, and to my mind, this is what decision that we're faced with.

610
01:06:15,443 --> 01:06:18,965
[SPEAKER_01]: The only thing I would add to that is if in fact

611
01:06:20,178 --> 01:06:32,767
[SPEAKER_01]: commission decided to go with a ladder suggestion to unload that piece of work, that again, it would be only a recommendation and the final authority is the commission.

612
01:06:34,528 --> 01:06:40,011
[SPEAKER_01]: Accept it totally, accept a few pieces, reject it totally.

613
01:06:40,452 --> 01:06:42,593
[SPEAKER_01]: That would entirely be up to the commission.

614
01:06:44,414 --> 01:06:45,015
[SPEAKER_04]: Thanks, Steve.

615
01:06:45,215 --> 01:06:46,476
[SPEAKER_04]: Judy, were you going to jump in?

616
01:06:47,476 --> 01:06:48,297
[SPEAKER_08]: No, I was not.

617
01:06:48,317 --> 01:06:49,498
[SPEAKER_08]: I was going to mute myself.

618
01:06:53,378 --> 01:07:05,886
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, I, I kind of think that it's, you know, I think Rob did an outstanding job and I think we definitely have opportunities to, um, to look at revising parts of the ordinance.

619
01:07:07,027 --> 01:07:19,796
[SPEAKER_03]: And I, and I kind of feel like didn't Francis share, like in the absence of a solicitor, she had named like a place where she could probably get some resources for us.

620
01:07:20,056 --> 01:07:20,416
[SPEAKER_03]: So I.

621
01:07:22,078 --> 01:07:38,627
[SPEAKER_03]: You know, I think it'd be great to spend some time on revising the ordinance as a commission, you know, and also getting some legal support from the city, which perhaps is available between now and when the solicitor is hired.

622
01:07:39,608 --> 01:07:45,731
[SPEAKER_03]: We'd love to see us as a commission create a calendar for the rest of the year since already April.

623
01:07:45,851 --> 01:07:49,794
[SPEAKER_03]: We're already, you know, finished with the first quarter of the year.

624
01:07:49,854 --> 01:07:50,354
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, maybe

625
01:07:51,272 --> 01:07:54,055
[SPEAKER_03]: next meeting, we can spend some time on that.

626
01:07:54,115 --> 01:08:00,260
[SPEAKER_03]: And if anyone wants, you know, and I'm happy to even try to start putting something together for us to react to next meeting.

627
01:08:00,280 --> 01:08:03,443
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you, Diane.

628
01:08:03,483 --> 01:08:05,084
[SPEAKER_04]: Gigi, you have your hand raised?

629
01:08:05,244 --> 01:08:05,965
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah, the St.

630
01:08:06,005 --> 01:08:19,617
[SPEAKER_09]: Medford committee may have access to some pro bono legal support, and also definitely has access to the city council, to a number of city council members.

631
01:08:20,226 --> 01:08:25,009
[SPEAKER_09]: One of whom has already expressed interest in a revised ordinance.

632
01:08:25,349 --> 01:08:27,110
[SPEAKER_09]: So just so you know.

633
01:08:29,032 --> 01:08:42,200
[SPEAKER_03]: And I noticed on Francis's agenda, you know, the city charter commission review, is that also, you know, is commission work part of that review as well?

634
01:08:42,220 --> 01:08:45,341
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't think it is.

635
01:08:45,682 --> 01:08:47,062
[SPEAKER_07]: No, that's a separate process.

636
01:08:47,223 --> 01:08:47,783
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, yeah.

637
01:08:49,991 --> 01:09:12,065
[SPEAKER_06]: So maybe then at this point, it makes sense to move for a motion to spend time during our next meeting to establish a calendar of events that the commission can follow for the remainder of 2023 and going forward to at least begin to organize our thoughts and efforts.

638
01:09:14,067 --> 01:09:18,890
[SPEAKER_06]: I am happy to make that motion here and now, which is what I'm doing.

639
01:09:19,645 --> 01:09:20,566
[SPEAKER_06]: That's the motion.

640
01:09:22,507 --> 01:09:23,747
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm happy to second that.

641
01:09:23,767 --> 01:09:25,508
[SPEAKER_04]: Love it.

642
01:09:27,849 --> 01:09:28,350
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you, Rob.

643
01:09:32,072 --> 01:09:34,513
[SPEAKER_01]: Sounds great.

644
01:09:34,533 --> 01:09:35,273
[SPEAKER_01]: Just hold on a second.

645
01:09:35,313 --> 01:09:37,735
[SPEAKER_01]: Could you restate the motion for the minutes?

646
01:09:38,515 --> 01:09:39,235
[SPEAKER_01]: The notes?

647
01:09:39,255 --> 01:09:41,737
[SPEAKER_06]: Be a bit more concise for you, Steve.

648
01:09:42,337 --> 01:09:47,560
[SPEAKER_06]: A motion to spend time during our next meeting building a calendar of events.

649
01:09:48,362 --> 01:09:53,804
[SPEAKER_06]: for the remainder of 2023 and to be used going forward.

650
01:09:53,824 --> 01:09:59,206
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you.

651
01:09:59,766 --> 01:10:00,386
[SPEAKER_04]: That's great.

652
01:10:02,987 --> 01:10:03,247
[SPEAKER_04]: Great.

653
01:10:03,387 --> 01:10:05,628
[SPEAKER_04]: So we have 15-ish minutes.

654
01:10:07,188 --> 01:10:08,069
[SPEAKER_01]: You need to take a vote.

655
01:10:09,029 --> 01:10:09,549
[SPEAKER_04]: Oh, vote?

656
01:10:09,569 --> 01:10:10,149
[SPEAKER_04]: Didn't we vote?

657
01:10:11,370 --> 01:10:12,190
[SPEAKER_01]: We have a motion.

658
01:10:12,210 --> 01:10:12,650
[SPEAKER_01]: Not really.

659
01:10:12,770 --> 01:10:13,531
[SPEAKER_11]: OK, sec.

660
01:10:15,331 --> 01:10:16,272
[SPEAKER_11]: All in favor say aye.

661
01:10:16,352 --> 01:10:16,432
[SPEAKER_11]: Aye.

662
01:10:18,182 --> 01:10:19,343
[SPEAKER_11]: All right.

663
01:10:19,363 --> 01:10:19,483
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay.

664
01:10:19,523 --> 01:10:19,823
[SPEAKER_05]: Yes.

665
01:10:20,323 --> 01:10:20,984
[SPEAKER_04]: There we go.

666
01:10:21,804 --> 01:10:22,264
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

667
01:10:23,965 --> 01:10:29,749
[SPEAKER_04]: Um, do folks have announcements slash new business comments?

668
01:10:30,909 --> 01:10:31,390
[SPEAKER_04]: Go for it.

669
01:10:32,090 --> 01:10:32,570
[SPEAKER_07]: No, no, no.

670
01:10:32,750 --> 01:10:37,413
[SPEAKER_07]: I, I, I was, I didn't know that you were going to seeking a new business.

671
01:10:38,213 --> 01:10:44,497
[SPEAKER_07]: I, I wanted the, the, the document that Francis send us where

672
01:10:45,517 --> 01:10:57,021
[SPEAKER_07]: It's a communication from the Mass Human Rights Commission group asking us if we are interested in endorsing that specific document.

673
01:10:57,081 --> 01:10:59,362
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't know if people have had a chance to read it.

674
01:11:00,422 --> 01:11:04,484
[SPEAKER_04]: Do you wanna share a quick synopsis?

675
01:11:04,504 --> 01:11:06,464
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, hold on a moment, please.

676
01:11:08,385 --> 01:11:12,266
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, so essentially, oops.

677
01:11:15,176 --> 01:11:26,906
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, so this is basically, uh, asking for endorsement for the Massachusetts indigenous legislative agenda.

678
01:11:28,027 --> 01:11:38,076
[SPEAKER_07]: And the four items I think are that are in there are an act prohibiting the use of Native American mascots by public schools of the Commonwealth.

679
01:11:39,017 --> 01:11:41,138
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm not gonna go through the rest of the verbiage.

680
01:11:41,699 --> 01:11:42,740
[SPEAKER_07]: The second one is

681
01:11:43,523 --> 01:11:46,645
[SPEAKER_07]: an act establishing an Indigenous People's Day.

682
01:11:47,846 --> 01:11:55,611
[SPEAKER_07]: The third one is an act relative to celebrating and teaching Native American culture and history.

683
01:11:55,631 --> 01:12:07,138
[SPEAKER_07]: And then an act providing for the creation of a permanent commission relative to the education of American Indian and Alaska Native residents of the Commonwealth.

684
01:12:08,219 --> 01:12:09,820
[SPEAKER_07]: And I'm sorry, there's actually one more.

685
01:12:10,960 --> 01:12:13,603
[SPEAKER_07]: an act to protect Native American heritage.

686
01:12:14,724 --> 01:12:35,164
[SPEAKER_07]: So I don't know if folks had a chance to go through this document and whether they're ready to discuss it or decide whether we want to include the endorsement of the Metro Human Rights Commission of these five issues.

687
01:12:38,653 --> 01:12:40,453
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm on board with endorsing it.

688
01:12:40,473 --> 01:12:43,314
[SPEAKER_12]: Okay.

689
01:12:43,414 --> 01:12:50,055
[SPEAKER_11]: It's an Indigenous-led organization, so I'm going to follow their lead, and I would be happy to endorse it.

690
01:12:51,495 --> 01:12:55,476
[SPEAKER_06]: I think just two quick points to raise that are in the doc itself.

691
01:12:56,036 --> 01:13:05,558
[SPEAKER_06]: Indigenous Peoples' Day would supplant Columbus Day, so I think that's something, given the history of Medford, it's worth at least saying out loud here.

692
01:13:06,550 --> 01:13:16,875
[SPEAKER_06]: And the other item was that there are 25 public high schools currently in the Commonwealth that use Native American mascots.

693
01:13:18,616 --> 01:13:26,580
[SPEAKER_06]: Putting that out there, that said, I fully endorse the commission to support the act as well.

694
01:13:29,581 --> 01:13:33,323
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, so do we wanna take a quick vote on endorsing this?

695
01:13:35,838 --> 01:13:53,981
[SPEAKER_07]: I'll put a motion that the National Human Rights Commission endorse these five resolutions and give me the authority to communicate this to the National Human Rights Commission who are actually meeting in a couple of days.

696
01:13:54,681 --> 01:13:55,722
[SPEAKER_11]: I second that motion.

697
01:13:56,402 --> 01:13:57,042
[SPEAKER_11]: All in favor?

698
01:13:57,842 --> 01:13:58,082
[SPEAKER_11]: Aye.

699
01:13:58,562 --> 01:13:58,702
[SPEAKER_07]: Aye.

700
01:13:58,722 --> 01:14:00,082
[SPEAKER_07]: All right.

701
01:14:00,242 --> 01:14:00,642
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

702
01:14:00,702 --> 01:14:01,743
[SPEAKER_07]: That's basically it.

703
01:14:03,083 --> 01:14:03,683
[SPEAKER_11]: Thanks, Muneer.

704
01:14:05,472 --> 01:14:10,956
[SPEAKER_11]: Happy to get rid of Columbus Day, just saying I'm as Italian, I'm Italian, but bye.

705
01:14:11,676 --> 01:14:13,858
[SPEAKER_11]: Say bye-bye Columbus.

706
01:14:17,420 --> 01:14:18,361
[SPEAKER_04]: Bye-bye.

707
01:14:18,601 --> 01:14:21,743
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay, great.

708
01:14:21,923 --> 01:14:26,266
[SPEAKER_04]: Do people have new business announcements, comments?

709
01:14:28,087 --> 01:14:34,612
[SPEAKER_07]: I have one thing to bring up to see if people are interested in this issue at all.

710
01:14:37,630 --> 01:14:52,986
[SPEAKER_07]: As of, I think, the 11th of next month, I believe that the so-called state of emergency or whatever it is that the federal government has declared for COVID is going to end.

711
01:14:54,187 --> 01:14:58,151
[SPEAKER_07]: Now part of this that may not have been advertised very much

712
01:14:59,330 --> 01:15:23,295
[SPEAKER_07]: is that there has been some pressure and apparently decisions have been made to remove the mask requirements in all medical facilities and in, what's the word, in retirement

713
01:15:25,259 --> 01:15:26,380
[SPEAKER_07]: homes communities.

714
01:15:26,920 --> 01:15:30,723
[SPEAKER_07]: So they are going to remove the mask requirements in these retirement communities.

715
01:15:31,083 --> 01:15:37,188
[SPEAKER_07]: And they're also going to remove the testing of folks who work there.

716
01:15:38,729 --> 01:15:51,859
[SPEAKER_07]: And some people think, including myself, that, you know, a lot of people are going to be affected by this, especially folks who have, you know, specific conditions, older people.

717
01:15:52,732 --> 01:15:54,552
[SPEAKER_07]: And this is a dangerous thing.

718
01:15:54,672 --> 01:16:14,976
[SPEAKER_07]: So the question is, I'm bringing this up here to see if there is interest in this commission to consider this and to take some action opposing this universal removal of mask requirements in all medical facilities.

719
01:16:15,736 --> 01:16:18,997
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm just interested in hearing people's thoughts on this.

720
01:16:19,797 --> 01:16:29,371
[SPEAKER_11]: Sarah Silver, PB – David Ensign – He, Him, His): unpopular opinion, but i'm i wouldn't i wouldn't be in support of that personally i i i yeah that's not something that I would yeah.

721
01:16:29,391 --> 01:16:31,854
[SPEAKER_05]: PB, David Ensign – He, Him, His.:

722
01:16:31,854 --> 01:16:32,255
[SPEAKER_05]: : yeah that's fine.

723
01:16:46,105 --> 01:16:49,006
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, there are no other comments and no other interest.

724
01:16:49,226 --> 01:16:53,487
[SPEAKER_07]: I will not pursue this within this commission.

725
01:16:58,428 --> 01:16:59,128
[SPEAKER_04]: Thanks Munir.

726
01:16:59,709 --> 01:17:03,049
[SPEAKER_04]: Guys, I have a much more micro announcement.

727
01:17:03,530 --> 01:17:12,652
[SPEAKER_04]: I have earned myself a spot at Tufts University in the Urban Environmental Planning Department and a full ride.

728
01:17:13,193 --> 01:17:14,274
[SPEAKER_04]: So I'm out.

729
01:17:14,474 --> 01:17:15,494
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm going to school.

730
01:17:16,875 --> 01:17:23,819
[SPEAKER_04]: So yay for Rob's June definition of timelines, because apparently I'll be here for May and June.

731
01:17:25,480 --> 01:17:29,423
[SPEAKER_04]: And I would love to think that this role has a little bit helped Tufts to notice me.

732
01:17:29,523 --> 01:17:31,144
[SPEAKER_04]: So I'm appreciating all of you.

733
01:17:32,264 --> 01:17:35,747
[SPEAKER_04]: So I don't know what that means for organization after June.

734
01:17:35,807 --> 01:17:41,050
[SPEAKER_04]: I know we don't usually meet in August, but I'm finally allowed to say out loud and publicly.

735
01:17:42,043 --> 01:17:43,464
[SPEAKER_02]: Congratulations.

736
01:17:43,584 --> 01:17:47,327
[SPEAKER_07]: Congratulations indeed.

737
01:17:47,688 --> 01:17:52,531
[SPEAKER_07]: So Chelly, does this mean that you will still be part of this commission or are you implying that?

738
01:17:52,671 --> 01:17:59,077
[SPEAKER_04]: No, no, I'm throwing myself into graduate school and I've been matriculated full time.

739
01:17:59,877 --> 01:18:00,518
[SPEAKER_07]: OK, great.

740
01:18:01,058 --> 01:18:05,602
[SPEAKER_07]: So so so the thing is that now this brings up the issue.

741
01:18:05,662 --> 01:18:05,862
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean,

742
01:18:06,752 --> 01:18:11,814
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't know what Frances's involvement is going to be.

743
01:18:11,834 --> 01:18:16,777
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean, she has not attended the last three meetings, I guess.

744
01:18:17,917 --> 01:18:27,081
[SPEAKER_07]: And I don't know whether the search or the effort to find new commissioners, I don't know where that is going.

745
01:18:27,101 --> 01:18:35,165
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean, should we be expressing some concern about that or should we be taking an initiative

746
01:18:35,860 --> 01:18:40,165
[SPEAKER_07]: to ourselves try and recruit new members.

747
01:18:42,538 --> 01:18:44,758
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, so just like a quick side note.

748
01:18:44,798 --> 01:18:52,400
[SPEAKER_04]: So there are a bunch of dates listed on the agenda, Interfaith Iftar, Couple Flag Raisings, Haitian Month.

749
01:18:52,800 --> 01:19:02,982
