750
01:19:03,022 --> 01:19:06,183
[SPEAKER_04]: And I might add West Medford Open Studios and Circle in the Square.

751
01:19:07,523 --> 01:19:09,385
[SPEAKER_04]: the list shared is certainly not exhaustive.

752
01:19:09,465 --> 01:19:17,951
[SPEAKER_04]: So I just, I would love to see us make use of spring and spring energy and folks feeling reconnected after winter for the first time.

753
01:19:18,011 --> 01:19:23,335
[SPEAKER_04]: And it might be a place where we could pull, if we could pull two or three folks out of 10 events, that'd be awesome.

754
01:19:24,096 --> 01:19:29,259
[SPEAKER_04]: So, and I imagine that we're all pretty involved people and we might be moving in those spaces anyways.

755
01:19:30,721 --> 01:19:30,961
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

756
01:19:31,061 --> 01:19:32,482
[SPEAKER_11]: And are they still doing pride?

757
01:19:32,702 --> 01:19:36,665
[SPEAKER_11]: We did last, I spoke at pride for the flag raising ceremony in

758
01:19:37,890 --> 01:19:41,251
[SPEAKER_11]: That might be an opportunity to also ask for people.

759
01:19:42,251 --> 01:19:42,591
[SPEAKER_11]: Totally.

760
01:19:45,032 --> 01:19:46,353
[SPEAKER_04]: But yes, I hear you.

761
01:19:46,593 --> 01:19:47,953
[SPEAKER_04]: Just all that to say, I hear you.

762
01:19:48,073 --> 01:19:50,054
[SPEAKER_04]: We're in need of numbers.

763
01:19:51,554 --> 01:19:57,036
[SPEAKER_03]: I love the idea of us trying to help recruit new members.

764
01:19:57,136 --> 01:19:57,976
[SPEAKER_03]: I think it's great.

765
01:20:00,577 --> 01:20:00,737
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah.

766
01:20:01,160 --> 01:20:03,281
[SPEAKER_04]: I mean, as long as I've been part of this, we've been online.

767
01:20:03,301 --> 01:20:08,303
[SPEAKER_04]: So it was really, it was like a special moment to just see folks in person at the Royal House.

768
01:20:08,383 --> 01:20:20,068
[SPEAKER_04]: And so I wonder if it might mean something to be, to have the opportunity to introduce ourselves in person and talk a little bit about what we're hoping to become one-on-one with people in real time.

769
01:20:22,889 --> 01:20:30,432
[SPEAKER_06]: Speaking of, did we, has there been any continued communication or was there any interest expressed out of the,

770
01:20:35,193 --> 01:20:37,814
[SPEAKER_04]: We don't know who would have received that communication.

771
01:20:37,934 --> 01:20:39,735
[SPEAKER_04]: Would that have been you, Diane, or?

772
01:20:40,275 --> 01:20:54,540
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, so I did request copies of the sign-in logs, but not everybody signed in and shared, you know, the number of people who signed in with

773
01:20:54,944 --> 01:21:03,952
[SPEAKER_03]: the city they were representing in their email was on the lighter side, but there were, you know, there are some people from Medford, but also including us who signed the law.

774
01:21:05,733 --> 01:21:13,219
[SPEAKER_03]: But yeah, I didn't, we didn't get any, anyone reaching out about the Human Rights Commission specifically.

775
01:21:14,560 --> 01:21:14,921
[SPEAKER_03]: Thanks.

776
01:21:15,361 --> 01:21:16,122
[SPEAKER_03]: Eileen, go for it.

777
01:21:16,922 --> 01:21:22,027
[SPEAKER_10]: Okay, so the first commission I ever served on was the Women's Commission.

778
01:21:24,664 --> 01:21:25,504
[SPEAKER_10]: in Cambridge.

779
01:21:26,244 --> 01:21:33,946
[SPEAKER_10]: And the way that I was recruited was the commissioners themselves went out in the community looking for activists.

780
01:21:35,006 --> 01:21:42,508
[SPEAKER_10]: And one of the commissioners approached me and said, you're an activist, would you be interested in being on the Women's Commission?

781
01:21:43,088 --> 01:21:44,608
[SPEAKER_10]: And I said, well, I don't know.

782
01:21:44,628 --> 01:21:47,809
[SPEAKER_10]: I don't know anything about it because it had just formed.

783
01:21:48,843 --> 01:21:59,568
[SPEAKER_10]: So I was invited along with other prospective candidates to a meet and greet in the city hall in the room where the commission meets.

784
01:22:00,309 --> 01:22:03,010
[SPEAKER_10]: And they had wine and cheese and crackers.

785
01:22:03,570 --> 01:22:12,475
[SPEAKER_10]: And it was just an opportunity to meet with everybody and hear about the commission and kind of get excited about it.

786
01:22:13,399 --> 01:22:20,969
[SPEAKER_10]: And then as a result of that, a number of us said, yeah, we'll be interested in being on the commission.

787
01:22:21,629 --> 01:22:23,832
[SPEAKER_10]: So then there was a ceremony.

788
01:22:25,247 --> 01:22:42,411
[SPEAKER_10]: where we could bring relatives and we were sworn in publicly and our picture was taken and put in the Cambridge Chronicle, which now we don't have a paper, but you know, I don't know what we would do about that.

789
01:22:42,511 --> 01:22:46,312
[SPEAKER_10]: But I think that was a very attractive process.

790
01:22:47,112 --> 01:22:50,273
[SPEAKER_10]: And what I've experienced in Medford has been,

791
01:22:51,433 --> 01:22:52,454
[SPEAKER_10]: you know, nothing.

792
01:22:52,474 --> 01:23:00,581
[SPEAKER_10]: I mean, for example, when I was on the commission for disabled people, the clerk came up, swore me in.

793
01:23:02,042 --> 01:23:06,365
[SPEAKER_10]: Then I walked into Neil's office and said, Neil, I just got sworn in.

794
01:23:06,906 --> 01:23:11,970
[SPEAKER_10]: And the first thing he said to me was, well, you know, the mayor doesn't want any trouble.

795
01:23:13,718 --> 01:23:17,259
[SPEAKER_10]: That was the process, which was really discouraging.

796
01:23:17,699 --> 01:23:39,163
[SPEAKER_10]: But I am suggesting to you that if we had a more attractive process, we're inviting people to a little meet and greet, and we told what you're about, and you got people excited, and they got some recognition, I think it would be a lot more attractive proposal.

797
01:23:42,455 --> 01:23:44,296
[SPEAKER_03]: I love that idea, Eileen.

798
01:23:44,356 --> 01:24:05,568
[SPEAKER_03]: And I wonder if in the same way that Francis was able to get some catering for the Belinda event in February, maybe we get, I don't even know, would it be the public library or where would the room be if we were to do that, you guys?

799
01:24:06,369 --> 01:24:10,411
[SPEAKER_03]: And I mean, we'd have to act on it quick because June is almost here.

800
01:24:11,102 --> 01:24:19,944
[SPEAKER_03]: So we really need to try to get people and get a date sooner rather than later.

801
01:24:23,805 --> 01:24:29,566
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, just thinking about the dates and the timing, I think there's also the fact that there does need to be.

802
01:24:32,187 --> 01:24:36,828
[SPEAKER_06]: If I'm remembering correctly, the process that I went through and also what's articulated in the ordinances,

803
01:24:37,610 --> 01:24:43,392
[SPEAKER_06]: Referrals need to be made to the mayor and then they appoint and that can take some time.

804
01:24:43,412 --> 01:25:02,921
[SPEAKER_06]: So yeah, just to your point, Diane, I think that if we do want to have, I think what I'm envisioning now, just very quickly thinking about it is that we would have folks we could recommend by June and then they would be appointed by our next meeting if we are still going to take that flight hiatus in the summer.

805
01:25:04,221 --> 01:25:06,022
[SPEAKER_06]: So that in mind, just to

806
01:25:06,668 --> 01:25:08,889
[SPEAKER_06]: drive over your point, yeah, we would have to act quickly.

807
01:25:08,909 --> 01:25:12,711
[SPEAKER_06]: I do know that there's tons of events coming up around the area.

808
01:25:13,111 --> 01:25:17,113
[SPEAKER_06]: Chief, I think there's one at the station there in the next couple of weeks.

809
01:25:17,173 --> 01:25:19,194
[SPEAKER_06]: That could be a great opportunity as well.

810
01:25:20,515 --> 01:25:23,456
[SPEAKER_06]: And I think, you know, there's nine people on the call here.

811
01:25:23,476 --> 01:25:34,762
[SPEAKER_06]: There's certainly plenty of platforms for amplification of messages, whether that be Facebook or the commission page or Patch sends out some,

812
01:25:36,392 --> 01:25:39,353
[SPEAKER_06]: notifications you need to the neighborhood or next door.

813
01:25:39,373 --> 01:25:41,833
[SPEAKER_06]: I think those are all great places to start.

814
01:25:42,273 --> 01:25:55,435
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't know what the process is for formally getting involved to be at events like the one coming up at the police station, or if it is as simple as wearing something that says, ask me about the HRC and just physically being there.

815
01:25:55,455 --> 01:25:58,336
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm just- Thanks, Travis.

816
01:26:01,596 --> 01:26:02,797
[SPEAKER_04]: Steve, go for it.

817
01:26:02,877 --> 01:26:05,177
[SPEAKER_04]: Are we okay to stay for three or four additional minutes?

818
01:26:05,809 --> 01:26:09,230
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, very quickly, I just wanna support Rob's comment.

819
01:26:10,150 --> 01:26:24,475
[SPEAKER_01]: France is included in the agenda, several events that are coming up in the city that in the past, the HRC has been involved, but those might be great opportunities to do that.

820
01:26:25,475 --> 01:26:30,937
[SPEAKER_01]: They're coming up soon, April 16th, April 29th, and then one in May.

821
01:26:32,087 --> 01:26:33,348
[SPEAKER_01]: and a couple in June as well.

822
01:26:34,029 --> 01:26:51,423
[SPEAKER_01]: And that might be good opportunities, and I love the button idea, but that would require making them and assembling at least a flyer or something that folks could walk away with about what the HRC is.

823
01:26:52,123 --> 01:26:54,425
[SPEAKER_01]: So I think there are plenty of opportunities to do that.

824
01:26:54,986 --> 01:26:57,068
[SPEAKER_01]: It just requires a little preparation.

825
01:26:58,729 --> 01:27:00,891
[SPEAKER_07]: Just one clarification.

826
01:27:01,715 --> 01:27:04,117
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, we cannot recommend to the mayor.

827
01:27:04,377 --> 01:27:05,457
[SPEAKER_07]: There is a procedure.

828
01:27:05,517 --> 01:27:12,442
[SPEAKER_07]: They have to go to the website and fill in an application and indicate that they are interested in the Human Rights Commission.

829
01:27:12,482 --> 01:27:13,462
[SPEAKER_07]: So that's a minor thing.

830
01:27:16,164 --> 01:27:19,166
[SPEAKER_01]: And I'd like to, I know we're over time, but I'd like to say one last thing.

831
01:27:19,206 --> 01:27:28,692
[SPEAKER_01]: It's a different event that was brought to my attention by someone from the Massachusetts Human Rights Coalition.

832
01:27:31,021 --> 01:27:37,451
[SPEAKER_01]: In the past, Neil would attend and I think Munir has attended the statewide meetings.

833
01:27:38,092 --> 01:27:40,857
[SPEAKER_01]: They hold an annual meeting every year.

834
01:27:42,219 --> 01:27:43,441
[SPEAKER_01]: This year, the

835
01:27:44,942 --> 01:27:48,345
[SPEAKER_01]: But they hadn't done that during COVID.

836
01:27:48,765 --> 01:27:50,867
[SPEAKER_01]: But this year, they'll return.

837
01:27:52,048 --> 01:27:54,150
[SPEAKER_01]: These are held at the State House.

838
01:27:55,171 --> 01:28:03,858
[SPEAKER_01]: And this particular event will be around health equity.

839
01:28:05,368 --> 01:28:10,754
[SPEAKER_01]: with keynote speaker Michael Curry, who's from the Massachusetts League of Community Health Centers.

840
01:28:11,735 --> 01:28:25,388
[SPEAKER_01]: They were hoping that someone from, or more than one person from this HRC would join that event on May 19th at the Statehouse, begins at 10 o'clock.

841
01:28:26,129 --> 01:28:28,211
[SPEAKER_01]: It goes most of the day, but they're hoping that

842
01:28:29,464 --> 01:28:31,065
[SPEAKER_01]: people would come for at least part of it.

843
01:28:31,705 --> 01:28:47,809
[SPEAKER_01]: And something I learned from them is that Medford, the Medford HRC was the impetus for creating the statewide Massachusetts Human Rights Coalition.

844
01:28:48,209 --> 01:28:50,430
[SPEAKER_01]: I hadn't known that, but I learned it.

845
01:28:51,130 --> 01:28:51,430
[SPEAKER_04]: Cool.

846
01:28:52,591 --> 01:28:53,351
[SPEAKER_04]: Chief, close us out.

847
01:28:54,420 --> 01:28:55,341
[SPEAKER_00]: I thank you.

848
01:28:55,381 --> 01:29:08,008
[SPEAKER_00]: I think I should make this real quick, but we should all be looking at the surrounding human rights commission, uh, and how their websites and other established, because if we're looking for memberships, I believe one or two of them had like real estate agents should be on the human rights commission.

849
01:29:08,028 --> 01:29:09,749
[SPEAKER_00]: We're dealing with field housing.

850
01:29:10,369 --> 01:29:12,490
[SPEAKER_00]: Um, they have, uh, realtors on there.

851
01:29:12,991 --> 01:29:20,015
[SPEAKER_00]: It just might spur some ideas of what fields of, uh, employment and people that we may want to, uh, invite onto the commission.

852
01:29:20,095 --> 01:29:23,797
[SPEAKER_00]: So it might just, it might bring our, uh, our outlook, but I'm done.

853
01:29:24,360 --> 01:29:24,800
[SPEAKER_04]: That's awesome.

854
01:29:25,481 --> 01:29:25,701
[SPEAKER_00]: Great.

855
01:29:26,562 --> 01:29:27,522
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you, Rob.

856
01:29:27,823 --> 01:29:28,283
[SPEAKER_04]: Amazing.

857
01:29:28,343 --> 01:29:32,927
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you so much for the work that you put into creating your document and presenting and sharing.

858
01:29:32,967 --> 01:29:33,867
[SPEAKER_04]: I really, really appreciate it.

859
01:29:33,887 --> 01:29:34,528
[SPEAKER_04]: I know we all do.

860
01:29:35,389 --> 01:29:40,833
[SPEAKER_04]: And thanks to everybody for staying a little late and all your big energy.

861
01:29:41,393 --> 01:29:43,635
[SPEAKER_12]: Much appreciated.

862
01:29:43,695 --> 01:29:43,955
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes.

863
01:29:44,436 --> 01:29:45,176
[SPEAKER_04]: It's time to go.

864
01:29:45,556 --> 01:29:46,297
